Operators¶

Operators are used to combine values. Java has rich set of arithmetic operators and logical functions.

Arithmetic operators¶

The usual arithmetic operators +, -, *, / are used in Java for addition, substraction, multiplication, division. The / operator denotes integer division if both values are integers and floating point division otherwise. Integer remainder is denoted by % operator.

In [1]:
5 / 2
Out[1]:
2
In [2]:
5.0 / 2
Out[2]:
2.5
In [3]:
5 % 2
Out[3]:
1
In [4]:
5.0 % 2.0
Out[4]:
1.0

Note that integer division by zero raises an exception, while a floating-point division by 0 yields NaN or Infinity

In [5]:
5 / 0

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
java.lang.ArithmeticException: / by zero
	at .(#16:1)
In [6]:
5.0 / 0
Out[6]:
Infinity
In [7]:
- 5.0 / 0
Out[7]:
-Infinity
In [8]:
0 / 0.0
Out[8]:
NaN

Mathematical Functions¶

The Math class contains a lot of mathematical functions thay you may need. To take square root of a number use Math.sqrt() method. First of all, you need to import this class using the keyword import.

In [11]:
import java.lang.Math;

double x = 4;
double y = Math.sqrt(x);
System.out.println(y);

2.0

To find the power of some number use Math.pow() function.

In [12]:
double a = Math.pow(2, 5); // 2 in extent of 5
System.out.println(a);

32.0

Math.pow() takes 2 double parameters and returns double as a result.

A Math class also supplies the usual trigonometric functions: Math.sin, Math.cos, Math.tan, Math.atan, Math.atan2

Conversion between numeric types¶

It is often necessary to convert one type to another. Legal convertion between types:

The six solid arrow denote conversions without information losses. The three dotted arrows denote conversions that may lead to information losses.

In [13]:
int a = 123456789;
float f = a;
System.out.println(f);

1.23456792E8

A large integer 123456789 has more digits than float can represent. When converting from this int to float we lose some precision.

When we do some calculation with different type, both operands are converted to a common type before calculation. If one of the operands is double, the other one will be converted to double. If one of the operands is float, the other one will be converted to float. If one the the operands if long, the other one will be converted to long. Otherwise both operands will be converted to int.

In [4]:
byte a = 1;
byte b = 2;
byte c = a + b;

|   byte c = a + b;
incompatible types: possible lossy conversion from int to byte
In [59]:
int c = a + b;
c
Out[59]:
3
In [60]:
int a = 5;
double b = 10;
var c = a + b;
c
Out[60]:
15.0

Casts¶

You saw that int values are automatically converted to double when necessary. Numeric conversions are possible in Java, but some information can be lost. Conversions in which information may be lost are done by means of casts.

In [63]:
double d = 9.9999;
int i = (int) d;
i
Out[63]:
9
In [65]:
d = i;
d
Out[65]:
9.0

If you want to round floating point numbers to the nearest integer, use Math.round() method:

In [67]:
double d = 9.9999;
int i =(int) Math.round(d);
i
Out[67]:
10

You still need use a cast after Math.round call, because it returns long value.

You cannot cast between boolean value and numeric types. This conversion prevents common errors. In case you do want to convert boolean to numeric type - use expression: isTrue ? 1 : 0;

In [1]:
boolean isSunny = true;
int isSunnyInt = isSunny ? 1 : 0;
System.out.println(isSunnyInt);

1

Combining assignment with operators¶

There is a convenient shortcut for asignment operations:

In [68]:
int x = 4;
x += 1; // equivalent of x = x + 1;
x
Out[68]:
5

Also you can use *=, /=, -=, %=

Increment and decrement operators¶

You can add or substruct one to(from) a number with the following shortcut:
In [72]:
a = 2;
a++; // a = a + 1
a
Out[72]:
3
In [74]:
int b = 4;
b--;
b
Out[74]:
3

This cannot be applied to numbers themselves. For example, 4++ is not a legal expression.
There are two form of increment operator: postfix and prefix.

In [76]:
int a = 4;
System.out.println(a++); // 4
System.out.println(a); // 5
System.out.println(a--); // 5
System.out.println(a); // 4
System.out.println(--a); // 3
System.out.println(++a); // 4

4
5
5
4
3
4

Relational and boolean operators¶

Java has a full set of relational operators. To test two numbers for equality, use the double equal sign, ==.

In [77]:
3 == 7
Out[77]:
false
In [78]:
3 == 3
Out[78]:
true

Use != for inequality.

In [79]:
3 != 7;
Out[79]:
true

Finally, you have standard >, <, <=, >= operators(greater than, less than, less than or equal, greater than or equal.

Logical AND operator is Java uses && sign and || for logical OR.

In [87]:
a = 5;
b = 7;
c = 7;
System.out.println("a > b -> " + (a > b));
System.out.println("a < b -> " + (a < b));
System.out.println("c >= b -> " + (c >= b));
System.out.println("a <= b -> " + (a <= b));

a > b -> false
a < b -> true
c >= b -> true
a <= b -> true
In [88]:
true && true // 1 * 1 = 1
Out[88]:
true
In [89]:
true && false // 1 * 0 = 0
Out[89]:
false
In [90]:
true || true // 1 + 1 = 2
Out[90]:
true
In [91]:
true || false // 1 + 0 = 1
Out[91]:
true
In [92]:
true || false && true // 1 + (0 * 1) = 1
Out[92]:
true
In [93]:
true || false && false // 1 + 0 * 0 = 1
Out[93]:
true
In [14]:
(true || false) && false // (1 + 0) * 0 = 0
Out[14]:
false
In [98]:
int x = 0;

if (x != 0 && 10 / x > 2) {
    // do smth
} else {
    System.out.println("Else block");
}

Else block
In [100]:
int x = 0;

if (x != 0 || 10 / x > 2) {
    // do smth
} else {
    System.out.println("Else block");
}
